UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 380
1 AN ACT relating to the forensic processing of firearms.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 SECTION 1. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 15 IS CREATED TO
4 READ AS FOLLOWS:
5 (1) When a law enforcement agency seizes or recovers a firearm that was unlawfully
6 possessed, used for any unlawful purpose, recovered from the scene of a crime, is
7 reasonably believed to have been used or associated with the commission of a
8 crime, or is acquired by the agency as an abandoned or discarded firearm, the
9 agency shall:
10 (a) Transmit to and receive from the United States Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms
11 and Explosives eTrace system and the National Crime Information Center
12 system information relating to that firearm; and
13 (b) Arrange for every such firearm to be test-fired as soon as practicable and
14 the results of that test-firing be submitted to the National Integrated
15 Ballistic Information Network to determine whether the firearm is
16 associated with or related to a crime, criminal conduct, any individual
17 associated with or related to a crime or criminal conduct, or reasonably
18 believed to be associated with or related to a crime or criminal conduct.
19 (2) When a law enforcement agency recovers any spent shell casing at a crime scene
20 or has reason to believe that a recovered spent shell casing is associated with or
21 related to the commission of a crime or the unlawful discharge of a firearm, the
22 agency shall, as soon as practicable, submit the ballistics information to the
23 National Integrated Ballistic Information Network.
24 (3) Local law enforcement agencies shall develop policies and procedures, approved
25 by the Justice and Public Safety Cabinet, for the recovery and forensic processing
26 of firearms and firearm-related evidence where a firearm was unlawfully
27 possessed, used for any unlawful purpose, recovered from the scene of a crime,
